5|$|From {{the end of}} World War II to {{his death}} in April 1985, Enver Hoxha pursued a style of {{politics}} informed by hardline Stalinism as well as elements of Maoism. He broke with the Soviet Union after <b>Nikita</b> <b>Khrushchev</b> embarked on his reformist Khrushchev Thaw, withdrew Albania from the Warsaw Pact in 1968 in protest of the Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia, and broke with the People's Republic of China after U.S. President Richard Nixon's 1972 visit to China.|$|E
5|$|In the Soviet Union {{during the}} 1950s, {{the head of}} KGB, Alexander Shelepin, {{proposed}} and carried out the destruction of many documents related to the Katyn massacre {{in order to minimize}} the chance that the truth would be revealed. His 3 March 1959 note to <b>Nikita</b> <b>Khrushchev,</b> with information about the execution of 21,857 Poles and with the proposal to destroy their personal files, became one of the documents that were preserved and eventually made public.|$|E
5|$|Novikov was {{released}} six years into his sentence following Stalin's death on June 29, 1953, and reinstated as Chief Marshal of Aviation, {{where he was}} able to put his ideas into practice. A plan for using newly available jet aircraft and nuclear weapons to wage a possible future war with the United States was laid out by Novikov and shown to <b>Nikita</b> <b>Khrushchev,</b> who turned the proposal down in favor of ballistic missiles.|$|E
